column18: You are being asked to volunteer in a research study. The purpose of the study is to better understand what everyday people think about politics in the U.S. If you agree to participate, your part will be to read a set of instructions and answer some short questions. It should take around 3 minutes of your time. Your answers are anonymous and handled with full confidentiality. There are no foreseeable risks or costs to you for participating in this study. Your participation is completely voluntary. You do not have to participate if you do not want to. If you have any questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, you may contact Ryan Bell at rwbell@princeton.edu. You can also contact the Princeton University Institutional Review Board at irb@princeton.edu. If you answer "I would like to participate" below, it means that you have read the information contained in this form and would like to be a volunteer in this research study.
column19:
The Irish,
	Italian, Jewish, and many other minorities overcame prejudice and
	worked their way up.  Black people should do the same without any
	special favors.
column20: Generations of slavery and discrimination have created conditions that make it difficult for Black people to work their way out of the lower class.
column21: Over the past few years, Black people have gotten less than they deserve.
column22: It’s really a matter of some people not trying hard enough; if Black people would only try harder they could be just as well off as white people.
